            "answer_text": "I\u2019m sure this won\u2019t be a popular answer but the unfortunate truth is that it doesn\u2019t compare particularly well, especially against the Army fielded in the Iberian peninsula some 40 years later. As with all armies, competency fluxes and the British Army at the time was at a relatively low point. It had been over a decade since the end of the last major war (the Seven Years War) and a lack of funding meant that manpower was woefully low. Despite the inevitable loss of experience in the ranks, the soldier himself was in good shape. While *probably* not at the same proficiency as Fredrick the Great\u2019s beloved infantry, he was still of a sound standard. Junior leadership was also decent but not excellent; company officers were often from the middle classes seeking a career and so took their profession seriously despite no (none at all) training beyond \u2018on the job\u2019. This is in contrast to regimental leadership and up which was embarrassingly poor. The regimental system of the time allowed the aristocracy to raise their own regiments in the service of the King and be given command. Their motives were rarely soldiering and so they often lacked the same drive for advancement which enabled their junior officers to mitigate their lack of training with study and application. Likewise, the system of purchasing commissions under the seniority rule compounded this; with the exception of battlefield promotions (for which there were no opportunities in peacetime) it enforced no soldiering standards whatsoever and led to a widespread capability gap at a senior level. It wasn\u2019t uncommon for Commanding Officers to be almost entirely absent from their command during peacetime and training above regimental level was none existent until well after the war started. It wasn\u2019t until the Duke of York\u2019s reforms some decades later that the British Army\u2019s officer corps was reformed. To add to all of this, the war was hugely unpopular and many officers refused to serve in America, preferring to resign their commissions instead. I\u2019m omitting the additional strain placed on the British by simultaneous war (without allies) against the France, Spain and the Dutch as this didn\u2019t affect the British Army in North America directly. It benefits both sides to enhance the notation of the British fielding the finest army in the world. American nation prestige is boosted by defeating such a powerful enemy while the British are able to look back at the period with pride in their military. While individuals and some units conducted themselves very well and my reply in no way diminishes or marginalises their actions, the reality is that British leadership in America was simply not up to the standard its reputation has earned and so, due to the importance of command, nor was the British Army. ",
