            "answer_text": "What makes you think that the Redcoats deployed to the American colonies were not Britain\u2019s best? During the previous 100 years, the British army had defeated many powerful countries in war, such as France and Spain, and seemed almost unbeatable. It was firmly in possession of India and North America, was better equipped than that of the colonials, was led by experienced and competent officers, and had a long tradition of winning wars.  The British army fought in Anglo-America was considered the most well-trained and disciplined army in the world. Since the end of the French War in 1763, the British army was intentionally kept small. It was a peace time army. The structure of the army was designed to have a small, high quality army that the government could supplement and expand in times of war. At the outbreak of the Revolution in 1775, the global size of the British army, excluding militia, consisted of almost 50,000 soldiers \u2014 not including \u201cGerman\u201d mercenaries, Loyalist regiments, or East India Company forces \u2014 establish in well-defined and well-articulated units \u2014 Infantry, Cavalry (Dragoons), Artillery, Line troops, Light Infantry, Skirmishers, Marines (amphibious units), Sappers and Miners, and support units. Nonetheless, the Ministry in London was corrupt and often at odds within itself in terms of overall strategy. It is unfortunate that the decade before the American war was a period of \u201cpolitical jobbery and corruption\u201d controlled by King George III\u2019s ministers and friends.  Thomas Gage, commanding 2,200 British soldiers at the Battle of Bunker Hill (Breed\u2019s Hill) in 1775, sent his men in frontal charges against these only to see the Americans kill or wound 44% of the British force. John Burgoyne would famously call the Americans \u201ca rabble in arms\" \u2014 and be defeated by them at Saratoga in 1777. It was inconceivable to most Britons that a group of colonial farmers, laborers, and mechanics commanded by \"pettifogging attorneys, bankrupt shopkeepers, and outlawed smugglers\" could defeat the greatest military force in the world at the time. Yet James Murray, an old friend and supporter of the former Prime Minister, the Marquis of Rockingham, noted, \"The notion of the provincials not fighting is very erroneous, and ... they have pretty good planners among them.\" Indeed, Gage may have been correct when he noted that the Patriots were \"not the despicable rabble too many have supposed them to be.\"[i]  [i] Richard Al. Ketchum, ed., The American Heritage Book of the Revolution (New York: Simon and Schuster, 1958), 248. See: Stand Alarmed, Militia in America 1607-1783 (Traditional American History Series 2nd Edition)  ",
