            "answer_text": "During that period the Red Coats were among the best, organized army in the world. Their smooth bore muskets had an aimed effective range of about 50 yards. There was only a front sight on their muskets, so in effect they simply pointed down range and hoped to hit an enemy troop. However, trained to use massed, volley fire, their two ranks could be effective at longer ranges, provided they had good, experienced NCO\u2019s who could command the troops to elevate their muzzles to the right angle upward, so the balls from the entire rank would fall into the enemy\u2019s ranks. They were in two ranks, so one rank fired, while the other rank reloaded. If their massed infantry fire was aimed correctly, they could break the ranks of the opposing infantry, before those ranks got off the first shot. The British discipline was such that the Red Coat ranks would continue to march toward the enemy, even as men in their ranks fell, dead or wounded. The rear rank were \u201cfile closers\u201d and when a man in the front rank fell, one from the rear rank filled the spot in the front rank. A problem for the Brits came if the opposing colonial forces had enough marksmen in ranks carrying Pennsylvania rifles. As the name implies, their bores were rifled with spiraling lands and grooves and spun the bullet down the bore at a much higher velocity. High velocity and the spinning bullet made for a long gun that went further with a higher degree so accuracy. Designated colonial marksmen were snipers and were charged with picking off British officers. Doing so could be very effective in stopping the momentum of a British attacking force. Some civilian guns were made for long range, having very thick, heavy barrels, that made it possible for the point of impact to hit in much tighter groups. They were best sniper rifles of that day. The value of sniping officers can not be over stressed. For a formations of soldiers of that day to lose it\u2019s commanding officer could in the right circumstances, spell the difference between winning the battle, or losing. ",
